
[1]plagiary

   PLA'GIARY, n. [L. plagium, a kidnapping, probably from plagoe,nets,
   toils, that which is layed or spread, from the root of Eng. lay. The L.
   plaga, a stroke, is the same word differently applied, a laying on.]

   1. A thief in literature; one that purloins another's writings and
   offers them to the public as his own.

   2. The crime of literary theft. [Not used.]

             PLA'GIARY, a. Stealing men; kidnapping. [Not used.]

   1. Practicing literary theft.
